@TateTheTalisman, your message resonates deeply. The courage you and @Cobratate have shown in the face of adversity is undeniable.

You've been at the forefront, alongside figures like #AlexJones , #TuckerCarlson, #Joerogan , and the #PBD2025  podcast, in exposing the deep-seated issues within the establishment, particularly the #WEF and what some call the "deep state." 

Your efforts have not just informed but have genuinely shifted perspectives, turning a generation of young men into patriots.

It's clear the battle has been tough - the personal sacrifices, including jail time, are testaments to your commitment. 

While there might be disagreements on specific stances or messages, your impact is monumental. No one can deny that you've been instrumental in sparking a movement, pushing back against forces that seek to silence dissent.

The call for unity and patience as we approach a new political chapter is crucial.

 We must remember the lessons of history; internal strife can be as damaging as external threats.

Thank you for your service to this cause. Your bravery in the face of real danger, the time served, and the relentless fight against those who would prefer silence over truth - it's all noted and respected. 

Here's to continuing the mission of shifting the Overton window, but let's do it together, with patience and solidarity.

Let's keep the knives out of our backs and focus on the real enemies.

It is somebody who does nothing to help anybody ever. But they save the world by telling rich people what their hard earned money COULD have been spent on.

For example although I spend millions per year helping people (something a poorlanthropist is both unwilling and unable to do) whenever I buy myself something nice they jump to the rescue with insightful takes such as;

"You're worried about what to name your boat while veterans are homeless on our streets!"

And so on.

The interesting thing about poorlathropists is that I know for a fact if somebody were to hand them 1 million dollars cash today that not a single penny would be spent helping anybody else. 

For poorlathropists no matter how much the wealthy try to help, they are always there to remind us to do better. When I handed out 100 dollars to every Vet who asked me for it I spend only 13,500 dollars because 135 people asked.

I'm am thankful to the poorlanthropists who reminded me after my merger giving spree that 13,500 dollars isn't much to somebody like me and I would like to apologise to all those veterans for only giving them 100 dollars in this difficult time.

Poorlathropists never seem to realise somehow that although they are poor, there are people poorer. They spend 100 bucks on food a week? Why not spend 50 and give 50 to Somali children? They drive a 10,000 dollar car? Why not ride a bike and give the 10k away?

One day I hope they wake up and realise that everybody on earth who builds any wealth ever needs to give all of it away all the time so nobody on earth ever has any money.

The poorlanthropist dream.
html:
What is a poorlanthropist you ask?

It is somebody who does nothing to help anybody ever. But they save the world by telling rich people what their hard earned money COULD have been spent on.

For example although I spend millions per year helping people (something a poorlanthropist is both unwilling and unable to do) whenever I buy myself something nice they jump to the rescue with insightful takes such as;

"20 grand for a lighter when there are kids starving?!"

"You're worried about what to name your boat while veterans are homeless on our streets!"

And so on.

The interesting thing about poorlathropists is that I know for a fact if somebody were to hand them 1 million dollars cash today that not a single penny would be spent helping anybody else.

For poorlathropists no matter how much the wealthy try to help, they are always there to remind us to do better. When I handed out 100 dollars to every Vet who asked me for it I spend only 13,500 dollars because 135 people asked.

I'm am thankful to the poorlanthropists who reminded me after my merger giving spree that 13,500 dollars isn't much to somebody like me and I would like to apologise to all those veterans for only giving them 100 dollars in this difficult time.

Poorlathropists never seem to realise somehow that although they are poor, there are people poorer. They spend 100 bucks on food a week? Why not spend 50 and give 50 to Somali children? They drive a 10,000 dollar car? Why not ride a bike and give the 10k away?

One day I hope they wake up and realise that everybody on earth who builds any wealth ever needs to give all of it away all the time so nobody on earth ever has any money.

The poorlanthropist dream.
